{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6efa7e02-dd29-40bb-ae43-7c19deffda99","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nFiles are named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_MachineName.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions). Open them with any text editor — they contain the stack trace, exception type, and register state.\n\n**To get a core dump** instead, run before launching your app:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nCore files typically land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can then inspect with `lldb`:\n\n```bash\nlldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./YourApp\n```\n\n> **Tip:** Apple's **Console.app** → *Crash Reports* also provides a GUI for browsing these reports.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8e769858-78ae-4619-89a1-fd4e1e7d9a8d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":295},"id":"9453baa7-deee-4d06-ab0e-0531c39905ef","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:01:58.830Z","parentId":"b2018437-9875-48cf-a56a-bd4a1570eacb"}
